Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: The Problem Manager is responsible for managing the lifecycle of all Problems. His primary objectives are to prevent Incidents from happening, and to minimize the impact of Incidents that cannot be prevented. To this purpose he maintains information about Known Errors and Workarounds.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: The Problem Record contains all details of a Problem, documenting the history of the Problem from detection to resolution.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: The Known Error Database (KEDB) is created by Problem Management and used by Incident and Problem Management to manage all Known Error Records.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: An Incident Model contains the pre-defined steps that should be taken for dealing with a particular type of Incident. This is a way to ensure that routinely occurring Incidents are handled efficiently and effectively.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: To identify the underlying root cause of a Problem and initiate the most appropriate and economical Problem solution. If possible, a temporary Workaround is supplied.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: To manage the lifecycle of all Incidents. The primary objective of Incident Management is to return the IT service to users as quickly as possible.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: To ensure that the other Service Management processes as well as IT Management are informed of outstanding Problems, their processing-status and existing Workarounds.
Prop.Label: Description

Prop.Name: sys_Description
Prop.Value: To use methods from quality management in order to learn from past successes and failures. The CSI process implements a closed-loop feedback system as specified in ISO 20000 as a means to continually improve the effectiveness and efficiency of IT services and processes.
Prop.Label: Description
